  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "On the less technical, more intuitive side of the spectrum, (1) template-based techniques provide standard chart types in pre-defined templates of existing authoring tools [33,46,47,75].",
    "However, such techniques typically offer limited customization options.",
    "(2) Example-based techniques are a related approach where the user submits an example, and the system provides a reusable template for further use, as demonstrated with AutoGosling [76].",
    "(3) Shelf configuration provides users more flexibility in creating bindings between data and visual encoding, often with the use of drag-and-drop interactions.",
    "While the template approach is mostly employed in the visualization creation and encoding mapping tasks, shelf configuration can go beyond that to enable finegrained alternatives between different encodings [13,54,60,75]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
